        <h2 id="examples">Real Google Discover examples</h2>
        <p>Three cases that show how different businesses use Discover to generate traffic that organic search cannot replicate.</p>

        <h3>1. Roofing company capitalizes on a weather event</h3>
        <p>A Texas roofing company published an article titled "What the 2026 Texas Hailstorm Means for Your Roof" on the day of a major weather event. The article featured a 1,400px featured image and a compelling headline with no clickbait. Discover picked it up and served it to Texas users with demonstrated home maintenance interest. The article generated 18,000 clicks in three days — more than the company's entire prior month of organic search traffic combined.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B SaaS earns Discover pickup for evergreen guides</h3>
        <p>A project management software company consistently published in-depth guides on remote work, team productivity, and project planning — topics their target buyers actively research. Several guides earned recurring Discover pickup, driving 5,000-10,000 additional visits per month that would not have come through keyword-targeted search alone. The traffic was consistently higher-quality than average organic visits, with longer session durations.</p>

        <h3>3. Food blogger blocked by image size</h3>
        <p>A food blogger with strong organic traffic and excellent recipes never appeared in Discover — despite writing content that matched exactly what Discover users engage with. The problem: featured images were 400px wide and lit poorly. A competitor with identical content quality but 1,400px professionally lit photos captured 40% of their category traffic from Discover. After upgrading image standards, the blogger began earning Discover pickup within three weeks.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Google Discover vs. Google Search — how they differ</h2>
        <p>The two surfaces share Google's infrastructure but serve fundamentally different user journeys.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Google Discover</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>No user query required — Google pushes content to users</li>
              <li>Ranked by interest match and freshness, not keyword relevance</li>
              <li>Traffic is spiky and unpredictable — viral potential is high</li>
              <li>Large images are required — 1200px minimum</li>
              <li>Tracked in Search Console under the Discover report</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Google Search</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>User types a specific query to trigger results</li>
              <li>Ranked by relevance, authority, and hundreds of signals</li>
              <li>Traffic is steady and keyword-driven — predictable volume</li>
              <li>Images helpful but not required for most query types</li>
              <li>Tracked in Search Console under the Search Results report</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for Google Discover optimization</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Use large, high-quality featured images.</strong> This is the single biggest technical barrier to Discover inclusion. Google requires at least 1200px width. Also add <code>max-image-preview:large</code> to your meta robots tag — without it, Google cannot display large image previews even if you have them.</li>
          <li><strong>Write compelling headlines without clickbait.</strong> Discover's algorithm penalizes misleading titles. Headlines should spark genuine interest and accurately represent the content. "7 Tax Changes Hitting Small Businesses in 2026" works; "You Won't BELIEVE These Tax Changes" gets suppressed.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish consistently on focused topic clusters.</strong> Discover rewards sites that regularly produce content matching user interest patterns. A single article rarely triggers repeated Discover pickup. Thirty well-structured articles on a focused topic over three months will.</li>
          <li><strong>Strengthen E-E-A-T signals.</strong> Discover favors authoritative sources. Author bios with credentials, expert citations, visible research, and strong brand signals all contribute to Discover favorability — the same signals that benefit organic search.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor your Discover report weekly.</strong> Google Search Console shows which articles received Discover impressions and clicks, along with CTR. Review this data weekly to identify which topics and content formats your audience engages with most in the feed.</li>
          <li><strong>Combine timeliness with your core topic.</strong> The highest-performing Discover content connects a current event or trend to an audience's established interest area. A roofing company article about a local hailstorm outperforms a generic "how to maintain your roof" guide because it intersects timeliness with demonstrated local home interest.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — relying on Discover as a stable traffic source</div>
          <p>Discover traffic is fundamentally unpredictable. An article can go from zero to 20,000 visits in a day — and back to zero the following week. Do not build revenue projections around Discover volume. Treat it as a traffic multiplier on top of your organic search baseline, not a replacement for it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Google Discover mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Publishing small featured images</strong> — anything under 1200px wide effectively disqualifies your page from Discover consideration</li>
          <li><strong>Not adding max-image-preview:large</strong> — even large images need this meta tag for Google to use them in Discover cards</li>
          <li><strong>Using clickbait headlines</strong> — Discover's quality systems suppress content with misleading titles; this also damages long-term domain trust signals</li>
          <li><strong>Expecting keyword targeting to drive Discover pickup</strong> — Discover does not work like search; keyword density has no bearing on whether your content appears in the feed</li>
          <li><strong>Not tracking Discover separately in Search Console</strong> — Discover and Search results data are separate reports; conflating them obscures what is actually driving traffic</li>
        </ul>

